If it helps as inspiration -- rgdd's tlog elevator pitch:

A list, typically append only.  Hosted by a single party, think database.  In
theory anyone can talk to the single central party and see what's in the list,
to detect issues (give examples -- basically what a monitor could do).  Not a
great setup though -- what if the single party show different answers to
different people?  To solve this we add cryptographic glue to to the list.
Called a transparency log. Now we can 'trust but verify'.  Tamper evidence.
Detection, deterrance. Not prevention.  Now 'monitoring' can be secure.  fyi,
it is possible to transform the list to a dictionary so don't worry about it.

Then if I have time, i'd take a step back and introduce claims and witnessing
(as the thing that adds security).  And maybe talk about the Merkle tree props.
Followed by Merkle tree.  But this stuff, usually not in the initial elevator
pitch and comes after.  Or well, claims are sometimes in the pitch depending on
how the basic monitoring examples are mentioned.  So that's where I'd work that
in quickly.

